        <bioghist id="ref1">
            <head>Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Born in Nyirpilis, Hungary on December of 1938, Nicholas Czunas became one of Hungary’s heroic freedom fighters. On his own since the early age of 14, Mikloas, as friends knew him, acquired his initial military and combat training as a freedom fighter during the Hungarian Revolution of 1956. After immigrating to America Nicholas was drafted by the United States military on April 12, 1962 and served in the U.S. Army Infantry until his discharge on April 10, 1964. Private First Class Czunas was assigned to Fort Dix in New Jersey for Basic Training and Advanced Infantry Training (AIT). From there it was on to Oakland, California followed by Yokohama, Japan and finally to North Korea. During his stint at Camp Casey in North Korea, PFC Czunas became a member of the 7th Division’s soccer team, competing against both American and Korean teams.</p>
        </bioghist>
        <scopecontent id="ref2">
            <head>Scope Note</head>
            <p>This collection details Nicholas Czunas early experiences as a freedom fighter in Hungary which helped to prepare him for his tour of duty in North Korea. An oral history interview was conducted on January 22, 2004 at Central Connecticut State University by Eileen Hurst, Assistant Director of the Center for Public Policy and Social Research, CCSU. Along with Nicholas’ taped interview, the collection digitized copies of a State of Connecticut Proclamation and a news clipping. The contents of the oral history interview provide evidence of American Infantry training, the daily routine of American Border Guards during the Korean War, and the management of military sporting teams.</p>
        </scopecontent>
